Task 6

Suppose you are interested in analyzing the popularity of each day (e.g., Monday, Sunday) in terms of sales.

Calculate the (1) median day sales and (2) overall total day sales for each day (e.g., Monday, Sunday). Save the resulting table (data frame) as day_analysis. Print a sample of day_analysis using head() or glimpse().

# place your code below
day_analysis <- daily_sales |>
  group_by(day) |>
  summarise(median_day_sales = median(sales),
            total_day_sales = sum(sales))
day_analysis
# A tibble: 7 Ã 3

2 Monday                261.           1054.
3 Saturday              463.           1701.
4 Sunday                297.           1355.
5 Thursday              268.           1336.
6 Tuesday               247.           1467.
7 Wednesday             252.           1288.

Task 7

Using day_analysis, create a geom_point() plot with x as the median sales and y as the day. Make sure to label the x-axis with âMedian sales for October 2024 ($)â and the y-axis as âDayâ.

# place your code below
ggplot(day_analysis, aes(x = median_day_sales, y = day)) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Median sales for October 2024 ($)",
       y = "Day")

Task 8

The plot you created in Task 7 alphabetized the day (from A to Z) which is not the usual ordering of the days within a week. Now, let us convert the day variable into factor with the correct levels.

Using day_analysis, create day_analysis_v2 after converting the day variable into factor with the correct levels. For the purpose of this exercise, start your level with âMondayâ.

# place your code below
day_level_vector <- c("Monday", "Tuesday", "Wednesday", "Thursday", "Friday", "Saturday", "Sunday")
day_analysis_v2 <- day_analysis |>
  mutate(day = factor(day, levels = day_level_vector))
day_analysis_v2

Task 10

Using day_analysis_v2, create a geom_point() plot with x as the median sales and y as the day. Make sure to label the x-axis with âMedian sales for October 2024 ($)â and the y-axis as âDayâ.

This time, however, use fct_reorder() to order the days within your plot based on which days have the highest values for median_day_sales.

# place your code below
ggplot(day_analysis_v2, aes(x = median_day_sales, y = fct_reorder(day, median_day_sales))) +
  geom_point() +
  labs(x = "Median sales for October 2024 ($)",
       y = "Day")

Task 11

Using daily_sales, use day with fct_recode to recode day as either Weekend or Weekday. Monday-Friday should be re-coded as âWeekdayâ while Saturday-Sunday should be re-coded as âWeekendâ. Save the resulting recoded table (data frame) as day_analysis_v3 in your R environment. Print a sample of day_analysis_v3 using head() or glipmse() below too.

# place your code below
day_analysis_v3 <- daily_sales |>
  mutate(day = fct_recode(day, 
                         "Weekend" = "Saturday",
                         "Weekend" = "Sunday",

                         "Weekday" = "Thursday",
                         "Weekday" = "Friday"))
